            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Brendan Scott\u2019s appreciation for permanence began in Portland, Maine, where the salt-laced air and steadfast brick architecture felt ancient and reassuring. As the only child of a high school history teacher and a city librarian, his upbringing was a quiet immersion in stories and structures. Family vacations were never to theme parks but to historical sites, where his father would narrate battles and his mother would point out the architectural details of centuries-old buildings.\n\nThis foundation led him to pursue architecture, first at RISD and then a graduate degree at UCLA, where the sprawling modernity of Los Angeles felt both thrilling and disorienting. He began his career at a corporate firm, designing sleek but soulless office towers. The work was prestigious but left him cold. A turning point came when his firm took on a small community gallery renovation. Brendan found himself utterly captivated by the challenge of designing a space meant to inspire public awe and contemplation. He quit his job within a year, dedicating himself to museum and exhibition design.\n\nHe moved to San Francisco at 32, drawn by the city\u2019s eccentric character and rich cultural fabric. A painful breakup a few years later cemented his relationship with the city; SF became his constant companion. Today, at 42, his life is a study in deliberate composition. He lives in a meticulously organized Hayes Valley apartment, his commute a 3.8-mile ride on the Muni bus to his SoMa office. As a Senior Project Manager, he navigates the complex dance between client demands, historical accuracy, and artistic vision.\n\nHis evenings are often solitary but not lonely, spent sketching new concepts or enjoying a glass of wine at a quiet neighborhood bar. His social circle is small, comprised of fellow designers and historians who share his passion. Brendan\u2019s ultimate dream is not to build the tallest skyscraper, but to lead the design of a new, landmark cultural institution in the Bay Area\u2014a space that will tell a story long after he is gone, a permanent contribution to the city that finally felt like home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He was ten, standing in the damp morning air at Gettysburg. While his father\u2019s voice narrated the ebb and flow of battle, Brendan\u2019s gaze was fixed on a stone wall. His mother rested her hand on it, explaining how the unmortared stones had stood for over a century. In that moment, he realized that the wall\u2014the silent, physical witness\u2014held a truer, more permanent story than any speech ever could. It was the first time he felt the profound weight and narrative power of a structure.\n\n2. Weeks after moving to San Francisco at 32, he took a ferry to Alcatraz alone. Standing in the deserted cellblock, he felt the chill not just from the bay air, but from the layered history of the place. He ran his hand over the crumbling concrete and saw the Golden Gate Bridge framed perfectly through a grimy window. The juxtaposition of confinement and freedom, of decay and iconic beauty, was overwhelming. It was then he knew this eccentric, complicated city was exactly where he needed to be.\n\n3. The silence in his apartment after the breakup was a physical presence. Feeling adrift at 35, he walked aimlessly, ending up at Alamo Square as the fog rolled in. He watched it swallow the city, leaving only the stoic outlines of the Painted Ladies. They were an anchor in the shifting gloom. The city wasn\u2019t judging him; it was just *being*, a constant and beautiful companion in his solitude. His relationship with San Francisco deepened from an appreciation into a quiet, mutual reliance.\n\n4. He remembers the quiet thrill of watching visitors at the opening of his first solo exhibition design. He stood in the back, unnoticed, and saw people slow down, lean in, and interact with the artifacts exactly as he\u2019d intended. A young woman paused for a full minute, captivated by a single piece he had lit just so. The feeling wasn't pride, but a deep, validating sense of connection. He had successfully crafted a space for public contemplation, affirming his escape from corporate soullessness.\n\n5. Every morning, his Muni bus turns onto McAllister, and for a few seconds, the golden dome of City Hall is perfectly framed by his window. It\u2019s a fleeting, predictable moment in his 3.8-mile commute that he treasures. The sight represents the city's grand civic ambition, its history, and its beauty, all woven into the simple, daily fabric of his own deliberate life. This small ritual grounds him, a daily reminder of the larger story he is now a part of."
